Figure 2. Multi-criterion kinemage of a 5-model NMR ensemble in side-by-side stereo, displayed in the KiNG applet. A small peptide (yellow) is bound to a short RNA hairpin (black), in Ô¨Åle 1BIV (38). MolProbity has highlighted steric clashes (pink spikes), suspect RNA sugar puckers (magenta T‚Äôs), outlier conformations of protein backbone (green) and sidechains (gold) and deviant bond angles around protein Ca‚Äôs (magenta balls). On the right side, KiNG has controls for turning on or oÔ¨Ä the individual models, parts of the molecules (protein versus nucleic acid, Calphas versus full backbone, etc.) and validation criteria.

New user interface and architecture
The internals and externals of MolProbity have both been signiÔ¨Åcantly rewritten since 2004. The outer face has remained centered around a single ‚Äòmain page‚Äô. To combat the added complexity of handling more than one structure, multiple NMR models and new analysis tools, the page is now more sensitive to context, displaying only the applicable options and even prioritizing them based on typical usage. It also features a ‚Äòlab notebook‚Äô that records what was done and the results, and a Ô¨Åle browser with diÔ¨Äerent kinds of results separated into folders.
The underlying architecture is signiÔ¨Åcantly more robust, and presentation is more cleanly separated from logic. This opens the door to multiple user interfaces that eÔ¨Éciently reuse the same underlying functions: from a web browser, from the command line, via web services, etc. Obviously, the web and command-line interfaces already exist; a web services interface will likely be provided if there is demand.
The molecular graphics program KiNG was also signiÔ¨Åcantly rewritten to improve its consistency and reliability. While outward changes are minimal, it is now easier to extend with custom plug-in modules, and its core can even be used as a standalone 3D graphics library in other programs.
Faster hydrogen optimization
The core algorithms underlying MolProbity have also been improved. The Snoeyink group at UNC has recently applied dynamic programming techniques to Reduce.

Hydrogen placement optimization is a computationally challenging problem. A general formulation of the hydrogen-placement problem is NP-complete, requiring simultaneous optimization of the placement of rotatable hydroxyl hydrogens; lysine or N-terminal amines; methionine methyl or methylated base hydrogens (but not aliphatic methyls, which are relaxed and best modeled staggered); Ô¨Çippable Asn, Gln and His sidechains; His protonation; and all movable hydrogens on het groups. The formulation is identical to that of the sidechain-placement problem (25,26). Such complexity usually forces software to rely on stochastic techniques, approximation algorithms or brute force enumeration. However, because Reduce‚Äôs scoring function is short ranged, the problem can generally be solved in polynomial time with dynamic programming.
The hydrogen placement problem may be formulated as a graph problem. In this graph, each hydroxyl, methyl or Ô¨Çippable group is represented as a vertex. Each conformation for such a group is represented as a vertex state. If and only if the scoring function for a pair (or triple, quadruple, etc.) of groups is non-zero for at least one assignment of conformations to the groups, then their vertices are connected by an edge (or a hyperedge of degree-3, degree-4, etc.). The complexity for a single problem instance depends on the connectivity of the graph ‚Äî speciÔ¨Åcally, it is exponential in the treewidth of the graph (27‚Äì29). Because Reduce‚Äôs scoring function deÔ¨Ånes low-treewidth problem instances, dynamic programming is able to rapidly and optimally assign conformations to groups (30).

